     {
      "QID": "1a-iii",
      "question": "Which aspects will you need legal approval for",
      "description": "See <a href='https://www.eeoc.gov/wysk/what-you-should-know-about-covid-19-and-ada-rehabilitation-act-and-other-eeo-laws' target='_blank'>here</a> for more information",
      "resources": [],
      "answers": [
        {
          "AID": "1a-iii-1",
          "prettyAID": "a",
          "answer": "Longstanding Exemptions",
          "description": "An employee who does not get vaccinated due to a disability (covered by the ADA) or a sincerely held religious belief, practice, or observance(covered by Title VII) may be entitled to a reasonable accommodation that does not pose an undue hardship on the operation of the employerâ€™s business.  For example, as a reasonable accommodation, an un-vaccinated employee entering the workplace might wear a face mask, work at a social distance from coworkers or non-employees, work a modified shift, get periodic tests for COVID-19, be given the opportunity to telework, or finally, accept a reassignment.",
          "resources": [],
          "nextQID": "1a-iv"
        },
        {
          "AID": "1a-iii-2",
          "prettyAID": "b",
          "answer": "Temporary Exemptions",
          "description": "Employees who are not vaccinated because of pregnancy may be entitled (under Title VII) to adjustments to keep working, if the employer makes modifications or exceptions for other employees.  These modifications may be the same as the accommodations made for an employee based on disability or religion.",
          "resources": [],
          "nextQID": "1a-iv"
        }
      ]
    },
     {
      "QID": "1a-iv",
      "question": "How will you validate the vaccination status",
      "description": "Unfortunately, there have already been identified cases of fraud relating to fake COVID-19 vaccination records. If you are concerned about this, you may wish to validate the vaccine records reported to your system.",
